      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Leafs",
        "body": "The Leafs' goaltender stared down the Flames' late rally Tuesday night, stonewalling Calgary's desperate bids in a <strong>3-1 victory</strong> that snapped a brutal six-game skid and ignited faint playoff whispers in a season gone sideways. At 54-16-11, they're perched first in the Central with 78 points&mdash;35 games behind the leaders, clinging to that elusive \"e\" clinch status and the 15th seed&mdash;but this 2-game win streak (capping triumphs over Edmonton and now Calgary again) feels like a gasp, not a revival. William Nylander's been the lone torchbearer, his sniper's touch burying chances amid the chaos, while John Tavares grinds quietly, both men dragging a defense that's leaked oil all spring. The ghosts of Vegas' 3-2 dagger on the 12th still linger&mdash;Toronto's collapsed under pressure before. Yet here they stand, unbroken if battered. <strong>Friday's clash with Seattle looms as the real test</strong>: win, and momentum builds toward the dance; falter, and it's back to the wilderness. For a franchise forever chasing April glory, this tightrope matters more than ever.",
        "updated": "Updated April 15, 2026"
      },
